52. Renumeret dotem huc,- eal] Phi- dippus says, ‘ If he wishes to take his wife back, let him. If he is not so minded, let him pay me back her dowry, and be off! According to Roman law the wife's dower became the husband's property, but con- tinued so only while their union lasted. In the case of separation, the woman, or her father, could bring an action forits resti- tution. Under the Greek law a similar provision existed.
